value.value: The dorsal extension of the scapulocoracoid above the level of the glenoid region in basal gnathostomes. Modified from Brazeau 2009.
Anatomical projections that are  elongate processes in the mid and posterior regions of the sternum.
Anatomical projection (crest) located dorsaly to the acetabulum.
Bony rim that is part of the supraacetabular region.

The route through which structures pass between the base of the neck and the posterior scapular region. It is formed by the suprascapular notch of the scapula and the superior transverse scapular ligament. From http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/suprascapular+foramen.
Series of fused cervical vertebrae or vertebral elements. Based on Jeffrey C. Carrier. Biology of Sharks and Their Relatives, 2012. CRC Press.

definition.value: 'The synarcual is a structure incorporating the anterior vertebrae of the axial skeleton and occurs in vertebrate taxa such as the fossil group Placodermi and the Chondrichthyes (Holocephali, Batoidea)' DOI:10.1007/s00435-012-0169-9

value.value: Axial subdivision that includes a series of fused cervical vertebrae or vertebral elements. Based on Jeffrey C. Carrier. Biology of Sharks and Their Relatives, 2012. CRC Press.
Facet for the articulation of the tibia on the astragalus (talus).
Anatomical projection on the anterolateral region of the proximal end of the femur.

definition.value: In Archosaurs was originally a possible insertion site for the m. iliofemoralis externus (Hutchinson 2001). In more derived dinosaurs this becomes a distinct process possibly providing the attachment surface for mm. iliotrochanteri in addition to m. iliofemoralis externus (Carrano and Hutchinson 2002)

value.value: A ridge or similar projection rising above the surface of an anatomical structure.
A part in the body of an organism that corresponds to an opposite symmetrical part.

A transverse flattened or cylindrical plate in the posterior body wall opposite the anterior ends of the pelvic fins, in front of the vent and at the posterior end of the body cavity, that supports a few anterior pelvic radials and a basal cartilage, the basipterygium.  from  Leonard J. V. Compagno. 2001. Sharks of the World: An Annotated and Illustrated Catalogue of Shark Species Known to Date. Volume 2.

definition.value: Potentially homologous to the pelvic girdle.

value.value: A caudal fin with three lobes.
Endochondral element that is part of the suspensorium sometimes ossifying distally as the quadrate bone and linking the basal section of the braincase to the lower jaw.

definition.value: The palatoquadrate cartilage is the primary element of the suspensorium in larval amphibians and can ossify distally in some taxa, becoming the quadrate bone. In mammals the quadrate bone becomes the incus.

value.value: Is a endochondral element that is part of the mesopodial skeleton and is contained within the prepollex which in some taxa appears as a pre-axial digit-like projection anterior to the first digit of the hand.

Is a endochondral element that is part of the mesopodial skeleton and is contained within the prehallux which in some taxa appears as a pre-axial digit-like projection anterior to the first digit of the foot.
Foramen found on the humerus of tetrapodomorphs beyond the entepicondyle and ectepicondyle foramen. Often denoted as foramen 'c' and 'd' after Jarvik 1996.
Sesamoid bone in the tarsal region.

A collection of attached ridges on the ventrl surface of the femur consisting of the internal and fourth trochanters plus the adductor blade and crest. Most notible in early amniotes (based on Romer 1956).

The median series of bones supporting the pectoral fin of sarcopterygian fish. See Dipnomorpha. In the pectoral fin, the first mesomere is the humerus, the second the ulna, and the third probably the intermedium. The radius is the first preaxial radial. All other homologies are suspect. from http://palaeos.com/vertebrates/glossary.
A scute parte of the basal surface of the fin in Sarcopterygian fish.
The space between the bones of the tibia and the fibula.
Process on the humerus of basal tetrapods, anterior to the entepicondyle and associated with subscapularis muscle (based on Coates 1996).
Process on the humerus of basal tetrapods, anterior to the entepicondyle and adjacent to process 4 of entepicondyle (see Coates 1996).
Process on the humerus of basal tetrapods, anterior to the entepicondyle and adjacent to process 3 of entepicondyle (see Coates 1996).
The area encompassing the radial and ulnar condyles of the humerus.
A bony dorsal extension of the clavicle.
The moon shaped fusion of distal carpals 1 and 2 found in some theropod dinosaurs, permitting greater wrist mobility.
The region of the astragalus/ talus that carries the articular surface for the navicular or central metatarsal.
The rough eminence which is on the anterior inner aspect of the neck of the radius and into which the tendon of the biceps is inserted. From http://www.merriam-webster.com/medical.
His roughened area of bone sits distomedially at the base of the coronoid process. It is the attachment site for the brachialis muscle. From http://www.anatomyexpert.com/.
A fossa on the distal humerus proximal to the entepicondyle.
